title: College football week 5 rewind
text:
Photo: Joe Buvid, For The Chronicle Image 1 of / 14 14 HIGHS
Around the area:
Houston quarterback Greg Ward Jr. set a school record for a quarterback with 182 yards rushing, with three touchdowns on the ground in the Cougars’ 38-24 triumph at Tulsa. Despite his outstanding showing with his legs, coach Tom Herman said Ward must work on the arm part of his gig – (“He missed some throws …”) – showing Herman’s capable of plenty of tough love even after a big win.
Photo: Joe Buvid, For The Chronicle HIGHS

Houston quarterback Greg Ward Jr. set... Image 2 of 14 TCU quarterback Trevone Boykin, who started the season a Heisman Trophy candidate and has bolstered the notion since, threw five touchdown passes in the No. 2 Horned Frogs’ 50-7 rout of Texas. Four of those scores went to freshman receiver KaVontae Turpin, perhaps a Heisman candidate of his own in coming seasons. Trust us, there’s also an area low from this game.
Photo: Ron Jenkins, Associated Press TCU quarterback Trevone Boykin, who started the season a Heisman... Image 3 of 14 No. 4 Baylor cranked out 499 yards of offense by halftime of its 63-35 whipping of fellow up-tempo member Texas Tech. While TCU had a close call at Tech a little more than a week ago, Baylor hasn’t had any en route to a 4-0 record. The Red Raiders playing the Bears to within four touchdowns has been Baylor’s “closest” call this season against so-far suspect competition.
Photo: Tony Gutierrez, Associated Press No. 4 Baylor cranked out 499 yards of offense by halftime of its... Image 4 of 14 Around the nation:
Florida crushed then-No. 3 Mississippi in Gainesville, Fla., as the Gators appear to finally be a program to reckon with (again) in the SEC East. Coach Jim McElwain is undefeated in his career at Florida (he’s only coached five games there) and the No. 11 Gators jumped 14 spots in the AP poll.
Photo: Rob Foldy, Getty Images Around the nation:
Florida crushed then-No. 3 Mississippi in... Image 5 of 14 Coming off a two-touchdown victory at Ball State, the No. 24 Toledo Rockets are ranked for the first time in three years. They finally crept back into the rankings by making Ball State miserable on Homecoming.
Photo: David Richard, Associated Press Coming off a two-touchdown victory at Ball State, the No. 24 Toledo... Image 6 of 14 LOWS
Around the area:
Texas coach Charlie Strong called his program’s 43-point loss to TCU “embarrassing” – in apparently choosing the most positive word he could come up with in such a situation. At least the Longhorns’ schedule gets a little easier (possibly) this Saturday. They take on No. 10 Oklahoma in Dallas, and if the Longhorns continue getting blown out by their Big 12 brethren Strong might not make it through the season itself – much less the offseason.
Photo: Tom Pennington, Getty Images LOWS

Texas coach Charlie Strong called his... Image 7 of 14 In a stunner at Rice Stadium, the Owls lost 49-10 to Western Kentucky. Rice turned over the ball five times – three fumbles and two interceptions – and the Owls now have 14 turnovers on the season. They had a dozen all of last year.
Photo: Elizabeth Conley, Houston Chronicle In a stunner at Rice Stadium, the Owls lost 49-10 to Western... Image 8 of 14 Around the nation:
Arizona State, already with its fair share of troubles this year, whipped then-No. 7 UCLA on the Bruins’ home field. UCLA dropped 13 spots in the AP poll as a result. Pac 12 play is off to an unexpected start – with Cal and Utah (of course!) the league’s only remaining undefeated teams.

“What I told them is we give you scholarships, we give you stipends and meals and a place to live, we give you nice uniforms. But I can’t give you guts and I can’t give you heart. Tonight it was BYOG – Bring Your Own Guts – and they brought some guts and heart, and they never quit until the last play.”
Clemson coach Dabo Swinney to ESPN on the field and in a pouring rain about his gutsy players following the Tigers’ 24-22 victory over Notre Dame at Clemson.

Leonard Fournette, LSU: The running back has rushed for at least 200 yards in three consecutive games, an SEC record, and is the far-and-away Heisman leader nearly halfway through the season. This time it was 233 yards on 26 carries in the Tigers’ 44-22 victory over Eastern Michigan.
Photo: Gerald Herbert, Associated Press HEISMAN WATCH
Leonard Fournette, LSU: The running back has... Image 12 of 14 Trevone Boykin, TCU: The quarterback has keyed the Horned Frogs to four consecutive games of more than 600 yards of offense, and didn’t even play the fourth quarter of TCU’s 50-7 defeat of Texas.
Photo: Ron Jenkins, Associated Press Trevone Boykin, TCU: The quarterback has keyed the Horned Frogs to... Image 13 of 14 Ezekiel Elliott, Ohio State: The running back already owns a national title with the Buckeyes, but apparently he’s not satisfied. He rushed for 274 yards in OSU’s comeback victory at Indiana.
Photo: Jay LaPrete, Associated Press Ezekiel Elliott, Ohio State: The running back already owns a... Image 14 of 14 College football week 5 rewind 1 / 14 Back to Gallery From Fort Worth to College Station, it was the Weekend of the Tweet in college football. First, Texas freshman defensive back Kris Boyd during halftime of the Longhorns' blowout loss at TCU retweeted a Twitter post suggesting he transfer.
"Our players should never be on their phone at halftime," UT coach Charlie Strong told reporters after TCU dialed up a 50-7 victory over the Longhorns. "I was not aware of that."
Boyd apologized for his tweet on Sunday. Over at A&M, sophomore receiver Ricky Seals-Jones was ejected in the first half against Mississippi State for a questionable targeting call. Later in the game and apparently from the locker room, he retweeted a post providing video of the hit.
Considering No. 9 A&M had defeated MSU 30-17 to enter its bye week undefeated, coach Kevin Sumlin took word of Seals-Jones' in-game tweet more in stride than Strong.
"We'll address that," Sumlin said.
A&M's fourth-year coach had plenty to be happy about despite his receiver's itchy fingers. The 5-0 Aggies enter a bye week to rest and recuperate for No. 8 Alabama's visit on Oct. 17.
Check out the gallery to see the highs, lows, Quote: of the week and Heisman watch for week five of college football action.
